text: I have so gotta see this!   I'll definitely be taking a large box of hankies as there is no doubt that I will cry during this movie. It looks really beautiful and makes me wonder what dogs truly do think about.   It also reminds me of the many canine friends I've had over the years: Scamp (Cairn Terrier), Czar (Staffshire Bull Terrier), Mackey (Scottish Terrier), Amber (Poodle) and Kirsty (Pikapoo). I have Ollie (English Spaniel) now.   Although each dog has actually belonged to an uncle or aunt and never really my own, we grew up together. I treasure each memory I have of them and hope to do the same with Ollie and, maybe someday, a dog of my own.

text: This movie is going to be a problem for me, I can tell already.  I come from a family of huge dog lovers.  They are the best.  However I cannot watch movies where the animal dies.  I can never watch I am Legend again.  Marlee and me, hell forget that. I never even attempted to watch that one. So here you have this movie. Looks like a great movie, especially for dog lovers.  The problem is not only would you be dealing with one dog dying, but essentially a bunch of them dying.  Now it looks like they don't harp on the deaths all that much by making them extremely sad. And of course you got the little added bit of knowing that the dog is not really dying but instead moving from one body to the next.   So maybe this movie will be safe.
